OL,3,CThings really do seem better in the
OL,4,Cmorning, scientists say
OL,6,FThe team, writing in the journal BMJ
OL,7,FMental Health, concluded: "Generally,
OL,8,Fthings do seem better in the morning."
OL,10,FThey also noted that people tended to
OL,11,Fhave more varied mental health during
OL,12,Fweekends while things were steadier
OL,13,Fduring the week.
OL,15,FFor the study, researchers looked at
OL,16,Fvariations in mental health
OL,17,F(depressive and/or anxiety symptoms),
OL,18,Fhappiness, life satisfaction, the
OL,19,Fsense of life being worthwhile, and
OL,20,Floneliness.
