OL,3,CThings really do seem better in the
OL,4,Cmorning, scientists say
OL,6,FDr Feifei Bu, from UCL's department of
OL,7,Fbehavioural science and health, said:
OL,8,F"Our findings suggest that on average,
OL,9,Fpeople's mental health and wellbeing
OL,10,Fare better in the morning and worst at
OL,11,Fmidnight.
OL,13,F"We drew on a large sample of repeated
OL,14,Fdata ` nearly a million survey
OL,15,Fresponses from 49,000 participants
OL,16,Fover two years.
OL,18,F"However, this pattern could reflect
OL,19,Fwhen people choose to respond to the
OL,20,Fsurvey, rather than a direct effect of
OL,21,Ftime of day.
