OL,3,CThings really do seem better in the
OL,4,Cmorning, scientists say
OL,6,F"For example, those already feeling
OL,7,Fbetter in the morning might be more
OL,8,Flikely to engage with the survey at
OL,9,Fthat time.
OL,11,F"While these findings are intriguing,
OL,12,Fthey need to be replicated in other
OL,13,Fstudies that fully account for this
OL,14,Fpotential bias.
OL,16,F"If validated, this could have
OL,17,Fimportant practical implications.
OL,18,FResearchers investigating people's
OL,19,Fmental health and wellbeing should
OL,20,Ftake into account the time of day
OL,21,Fpeople respond.
